The first Phantasmat (also by Eipix) was not, in my opinion, a vast success. It was a dark, twisted story that held my interest only briefly, and according to other  reviewers, I was not alone in that. Lots of folks liked it mind you, but it was too morose and maudlin for my taste. [Some time later] >>> Okay, well, it is (or appears to be) the end of the world, and anyone who hacks down a centuries old oak tree probably deserves to be tormented for a while --- if you can follow that logic and keep a good sense of humor (as in, "Seriously?"),  you might enjoy this game. And with dialog like, "Soon, you'll both become one of us" - you just have to laugh and wonder. Yes, it has most of the amenities (guide, a morph per scene, teleportation map and hints, HO's don't swap, and customizable but non-personalized difficulty setting, etc.). But, honestly, don't you think "Mr. Nightingale" and the "End of the World" are delightfully less sinister than an ancient High School Prom and a decaying Circus?  It's well made and a fine diversion. So it's simply a matter of taste. 8/22/2016.
